      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence study required with GCI < 5% on primary QoIs at MRL 2.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed using Richardson extrapolation. Fine-grid GCI values: shear stress scalar 1.8%, velocity magnitude 1.4%, NIH proxy 2.1%. All values below 5% threshold. Mesh selected: 8.4M cells (medium grid) as operationally representative with acceptable GCI."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must be documented with sufficient fidelity to permit meaningful comparison with simulation boundary conditions.",
      "rationale": "FDA PIV experimental conditions fully documented including fluid properties (water-glycerol mixture, viscosity 3.5 cP), pump speed (2500 RPM ± 5 RPM), and flow rate (5 L/min ± 0.05 L/min). Boundary conditions in CFD model derived directly from published experimental protocol. Temperature and fluid density matched within 1%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metrics (e.g., RMSE, mean absolute error, or validation metric V) must be computed and reported for all primary QoIs at MRL 2.",
      "rationale": "Velocity field comparisons with FDA PIV data are reported qualitatively through contour plot overlays and visual inspection of flow patterns. Numerical error metrics (RMSE, MAE, validation metric V) were not computed for the velocity field comparison. The hemolysis index comparison relies on percent-difference from mean experimental values without uncertainty propagation or formal statistical validation metric. While the agreement appears visually satisfactory and the 15% tolerance band is cited, the absence of formal quantitative comparison metrics means this factor does not achieve the required Gradation 2 level for output comparison under MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation must be directly relevant to the clinical decision (hemolysis prediction) and must be mapped to the COU acceptance criterion.",
      "rationale": "Primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) derived from scalar shear stress integration along Lagrangian particle tracks. NIH maps directly to the relative hemolysis index (RH) acceptance criterion. Secondary QoI velocity field supports mechanistic understanding of shear distribution. Both QoIs directly relevant to worst-case operating condition identification."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must be conducted on geometry and operating conditions sufficiently representative of the COU device and operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on FDA generic centrifugal blood pump — the same reference geometry used for COU evaluation. Operating conditions span the 5 flow-speed combinations specified in the COU. Fluid properties matched to blood analog. Validation domain directly overlaps with COU application space, supporting high relevance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
